article.description: Terrell Everett scored a career-high 26 points, including three late free throws, to help No. 5 Oklahoma stave off a late rally in a 62-53 win against Tulsa on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Everett's 26 help Oklahoma hold off Tulsa
article.linkText: Everett shelters No. 5 Sooners from Hurricane threat
article.story: TULSA, Okla. (AP) -- The last time Oklahoma played at Tulsa, the Sooners coach left with a vow: "We won't be back." After 20 years away, the Sooners returned and Terrell Everett made sure this trip was a more enjoyable one. Everett scored a career-high 26 points, including three late free throws, to help No. 5 Oklahoma stave off a late rally in a 62-53 win against Tulsa on Wednesday night. Coach Kelvin Sampson had a far different reaction than his predecessor, Billy Tubbs, did after the eighth-ranked Sooners lost 104-89 to an unranked Tulsa team on Jan. 9, 1985. Tubbs stuck to his promise, and it took until Sampson's 12th year for Oklahoma to make the two-hour trip to the state's second-largest city. The Sooners, playing their first road game, were greeted by a standing-room crowd of 8,555 fans that tied the Reynolds Center record set at a 2002 game against Kansas. "This experience was invaluable to us -- playing this team with this kind of energy, their backs to the wall," Sampson said after the Sooners (4-0) let their 19-point lead dwindle to eight before closing out the Golden Hurricane (1-3). Everett scored six of Oklahoma's points during a 10-4 run that gave the Sooners a 47-28 lead with 11:32 left. But with Everett on the bench for a brief rest, Tulsa immediately charged back. Deion James scored six straight points to bring the Golden Hurricane within 47-34 and Chris Wallace followed with a three-point play after Everett had returned. Charles Ramsdell dunked an alley-oop pass with two hands and Anthony Price brought the Golden Hurricane within 49-41 with a fast-break layup. The Golden Hurricane committed 16 turnovers in the first half, but only four in their second-half comeback. "One moment, we look like we're bumbling around like a high-school squad, and then the next we're hanging with a top-five team in the nation," said Ramsdell, one of only five Tulsa players returning from last season. "We're very young obviously. ... We're coming together, and you can feel it in the locker room after practice and you can feel it come together out on the court. "We're building right now." Nate Carter hit a 3-pointer from the left wing and a jumper from the right side on consecutive possessions to extend Oklahoma's lead to 54-42, and Tulsa's comeback chances faded. Everett hit three of Oklahoma's eight free throws down the stretch, and the Golden Hurricane never were closer than eight points. Sampson tempered his praise for the 6-foot-4 lefty because he also committed five turnovers. "Terrell is like the quarterback who throws six touchdown passes and three interceptions. Sometimes if you go trying to correct his interceptions, he may not throw a touchdown pass for you," Sampson said. "Sometimes we have to live with his turnovers." After putting the Sooners ahead 47-28, Everett missed his next four shots and committed two turnovers before grabbing an offensive rebound and going 3-for-4 from the foul line in the final 47 seconds. "He drives me nuts sometimes, but he's also a heck of a player," Sampson said. Preseason Big 12 player of the year Taj Gray played only two minutes in the second half before fouling out with 4:26 left, and it was Everett that took over for Oklahoma. Darold Crow and Ramsdell hit 3-pointers to cut into Oklahoma's 19-point halftime lead and bring Tulsa within 37-24 in the first four minutes of the second half. Everett drove from the right wing for a layup to start the Sooners' response, then added a floater from the left side and was credited for a basket on a goaltending call against Ramsdell that put Oklahoma ahead 47-28. Michael Neal scored 14 points and Kevin Bookout had 10 rebounds for Oklahoma, which got only five points and two rebounds from Gray. "Sometimes this game isn't about how good you are. You've just got to play smarter. You've got to adjust to things," Sampson said. "This isn't trigonometry or geometry. You've got two fouls? Be aware of it. You've got four fouls? Don't go clubbing guys." Crow, Ramsdell and Price scored 10 apiece to lead Tulsa. Oklahoma scored the first eight points of the game and pulled away with a 13-2 run that Neal capped with a fast-break layup to make it 23-9. Everett scored 15 of Oklahoma's first 30 points, including three layups off drives to the basket. He added a 3-pointer and jumper from just inside the 3-point line to extend Oklahoma's lead to 30-11 late in the first half. "He was great in the first half," Ramsdell said. "He was really killing us out there." Tulsa scored the next seven points, but Oklahoma answered with a 7-0 run of its own for a 37-18 halftime lead.
